<section class="section-divider" id="negatives">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">13</span> Registered failure № 1</div>
    <h2>If you just want volume, don't bother with rules</h2>

    <p>
      Line the careful, rule-following approach up against the crude alternatives, and a humbling
      truth appears: for <em>raw output</em>, crude wins. Simply flooding the model with constant
      writes makes the concept appear in <strong>96%</strong> of generations; the disciplined
      approach manages 16%. Six times less. The pre-registered throughput bet failed at all three
      seeds, and the evidence file says <strong>fail</strong>.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_l21"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 13"
      alt="Concept rate and cost across five approaches"
      caption="Five approaches, three-seed means. Left: how often the concept appears — flooding dominates. Right: the measured cost. What the rules buy is not volume; it's the next paragraph."
      gates={["gate_L21_baselines_seed42/123/777"]}
    />

    <div class="callout green">
      <div class="callout-title">What the rules actually buy</div>
      <p>
        Three things flooding can't offer: writes you can <strong>time-stamp</strong>, writes you
        can <strong>verify landed</strong>, and a <strong>metered freedom cost</strong>. If you
        want a firehose, flood. If you want something you'd deploy in front of customers — an
        audit trail, a defense — you want the rules. Act VI is that deployment.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="num-label mt-16"><span class="num">14</span> Registered failure № 2</div>
    <h2>The obvious safety trick does nothing</h2>

    <p>
      The field's standard move for making a model refuse harmful requests is to compute a
      "refusal direction" and push on it. Tested here as a sealed bet, on a model that already had
      safety training: attack success went from 25%… to <strong>25%</strong>. Exactly nothing.
      A companion bet on a "truthfulness direction": identical scores, steered or not. Both
      failures were reported in full — and both turned out to matter, because they redirected the
      project toward the idea that <em>works</em>: don't push always; <strong>recognize first,
      then push</strong>. That idea is Act VI.
    </p>

    <div class="num-label mt-16"><span class="num">15</span> Weakest link</div>
    <h2>The verifier is the shakiest rule</h2>

    <p>
      Rule four says: confirm a write landed by reading it back. Measured honestly, that read-back
      check is the weakest part of the whole system — it catches real writes at
      <strong>68%</strong> balanced accuracy in friendly conditions, drifts to 64% on held-out
      data, and falls to <strong>59%</strong> — below its own pre-registered bar — when pooled
      across writing styles. An adversarial reviewer forced the claim to be downgraded, and the
      downgrade stuck. Read-back is a useful <em>screen</em>, not proof, and every claim in this
      essay that leans on it is labeled accordingly.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
